04175nam a22007095i 9780691187808DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911878087 a10.1515/97806911878082doi  a(DE-B1597)501959  a(OCoLC)1076414916  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDG78b.C592 2004eb 7aHIS0020202bisacsh04a302.2/222231 aCorbeill, Anthony, eauthor.10aNature Embodied :bGesture in Ancient Rome /cAnthony Corbeill. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction. GESTURE AS A CULTURAL SYSTEM -- tChapter 1. PARTICIPATORY GESTURES IN ROMAN RELIGIOUS RITUAL AND MEDICINE -- tChapter 2. THE POWER OF THUMBS -- tChapter 3. BLOOD, MILK, AND TEARS: THE GESTURES OF MOURNING WOMEN -- tChapter 4. POLITICAL MOVEMENT: WALKING AND IDEOLOGY I N REPUBLICAN ROME -- tChapter 5. FACE FACTS: FACIAL EXPRESSION A N D THE NEW POLITICAL ORDER IN TACITUS -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX LOCORUM -- tGENERAL INDEX  aBodily gesture. A Roman worshipper spins in a circle in front of a temple. Faced with death, a Roman woman tears her hair and beats her breasts. Enthusiastic spectators at a gladiatorial event gesticulate with thumbs. Examining the tantalizing glimpses of ancient bodies offered by surviving Roman sculptures, paintings, and literary texts, Anthony Corbeill analyzes the role of gesture in medical and religious ritual, in the gladiatorial arena, in mourning practice, in aristocratic competition of the late Republic, and in the court of the emperor Tiberius. Adopting approaches from anthropology, gender studies, and ecological theory, Nature Embodied offers both a series of case studies and an overarching narrative of the role and meanings of gesture in ancient Rome. Arguing that bodily movement grew out of the relationship between Romans and their natural, social, and spiritual environment, the book explores the ways in which an originally harmonious relationship between nature and the body was manipulated as Rome became socially and politically complex. By the time that Tacitus was writing about the reign of Tiberius, the emergence of a new political order had prompted an increasingly inscrutable equation between truth and the body--and something vital in the once harmonizing relationship between bodies and the world beyond them had been lost. Nature Embodied makes an important contribution to an expanding field of research by offering a new theoretical model for the study of gesture in classical times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aGesture in literature. 0aGesturezRome. 0aLatin literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187808zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187808.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN